# UX Presentation Standards

When editing UI, HTML, or CSS, enforce these so the site meets professional presentation standards.

## Design tokens

- Use existing CSS variables from `styles.css` (`--text`, `--text-secondary`, `--bg`, `--line`, `--amber`, etc.). No hardcoded hex/rgb for colors or arbitrary spacing unless a token does not exist.
- Add new tokens to `:root` (and `html.theme-light` if needed) rather than magic numbers in components.

## Spacing and alignment

- Prefer a consistent rhythm (e.g. 8px base). Use multiples (8px, 16px, 24px) for margin/padding unless the design system specifies otherwise.
- Keep horizontal padding and vertical spacing consistent between similar sections (e.g. all content panels, all cards).
- Avoid single-off margins (e.g. `margin-left: 13px`) that break visual alignment with the rest of the app.

## Typography

- One logical `h1` per page; heading order must not skip levels (`h1` → `h2` → `h3`).
- Body text: use `var(--font-sans)` (or serif/mono where defined); ensure line-height ≥ 1.5 for readability.
- Secondary/caption text must use `var(--text-secondary)` or `var(--muted)` so hierarchy is clear.

## Interactive elements

- Buttons and links: minimum touch target ~44px (height or min-height) where they are primary actions.
- Every focusable element must have a visible focus style (e.g. `:focus-visible` outline or ring). Do not remove focus outlines without replacing with a clear alternative.
- Icon-only buttons must have `aria-label` or visible text/tooltip so purpose is clear.

## Consistency

- Reuse existing patterns: `.primary-button`, `.panel`, `.content-header`, `.music-link-block` (or equivalent) instead of inventing new class names that duplicate styles.
- Match existing pages: new content pages (e.g. movies, music) should share the same shell, nav, and block styles so the experience feels unified.

## States and feedback

- Provide hover (and where relevant active/disabled) styles for buttons and links so interaction is clear.
- Loading, empty, and error states must have explicit UI (message + optional action), not blank or unstyled content.

## Before shipping UI changes

- [ ] No layout shift or misaligned elements at common viewport widths.
- [ ] Text contrast meets WCAG AA (e.g. `--text-secondary` on `--bg`).
- [ ] Focus order and focus-visible styles work for keyboard users.
- [ ] New sections match the spacing and typography of existing pages.
